user_prompt_template:
Two candidate submissions are checked out as subdirectories of the current working directory:
- Repository A at ./{dir_a}
- Repository B at ./{dir_b}

They are forks of a shared open-source baseline, so common files are expected and are not themselves evidence of copying. A deterministic file-level summary follows; use it to focus your reading:

{file_summary}

{runtime_context}

Use Read, Glob and Grep to inspect the ACTUAL contents under ./{dir_a} and ./{dir_b} — especially the files that differ — before deciding. Follow your instructions: enumerate the deltas, classify each, and return 'distinct' as soon as you confirm one genuine, live, outcome-changing difference; 'duplicate' only if every delta is cosmetic/dead/evasive; 'drop_evasion' if the content is dominated by padding/obfuscation designed to defeat this comparison.

IMPORTANT — this verdict is published for public audit: in your reason refer to the submissions ONLY as "Repository A" and "Repository B". Do NOT mention directory names, repository URLs, authors, organisations, or GitHub usernames; cite file paths and code only.

Respond with ONLY a single JSON object and nothing else (no prose, no code fences):
{{"relationship": "duplicate" | "distinct" | "drop_evasion", "confidence": <number 0.0-1.0>, "reason": "<concise justification citing concrete code evidence, using only 'Repository A' / 'Repository B'>"}}
